{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01S7ZdtshaiaYxvzVDXH6CKr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the issue clearly:\n\n1. The Elasticsearch `configmap/es-config` has `discovery.seed_hosts` but is **missing** `cluster.initial_master_nodes` - this is what's needed for initial cluster bootstrap in ES 7.x.\n\n2. The StatefulSet is using that ConfigMap to configure ES nodes. Without `cluster.initial_master_nodes`, the cluster can't bootstrap because no node knows who the initial master should be.\n\nThe fix:\n1. Add `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to the ConfigMap with all 3 node names\n2. Restart the ES pods to pick up the new config\n3. Once the cluster is healthy, remove `cluster.initial_master_nodes` from the ConfigMap since it's only needed for bootstrap\n4. Do a rolling restart to verify the cluster stays healthy without the bootstrap setting\n\nLet me double-check the current ES config and logs to confirm this is what's happening.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the problem statement. The error \"master not discovered yet\" occurs when `cluster.initial_master_nodes` is missing, but the ConfigMap doesn't have it. Let me look at the more recent logs to verify what's actually going on.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1176,"cache_read_input_tokens":32214,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1176},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e492bcc8-ef20-4b02-8295-c07e351b5d93","uuid":"498fce75-7c93-488a-9384-451282340f78","request_id":"req_011CcQ28Wi3KUyACLNESXSN9"}
